<item>
 <title>Excerpt from Oregon Shakespeare Festival&#039;s Illuminations magazine</title>
 <link>https://kennedyprize.columbia.edu/winners/2013/schenkkan/page/excerpt-article-oregon-shakespeare-festivals-illuminations-magazine</link>
 <description>&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-field-teaser field-type-text-long field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;by Tom Bryant&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;Looking at Lyndon Johnson’s presidency in that light one can certainly see that Lyndon Johnson certainly embodies the expedient pursuit of power. Statements of his stand out as textbook lessons of the practical application of power: Public statement of positions, Johnson felt, were stumbling blocks to effective legislative action. He felt they tended to freeze men into positions making it more difficult to later accept compromise. “The process itself” Johnson said “requires a certain amount of deception. If the full implications of a bill were known before its enactment, it would never get passed.” On the criticism by more moralistic Senators of his behind the scenes deal making he said: “They are like a pack of nuns who’ve convinced themselves that sex is dirty and ugly and low down and forced because they can never have it. And because they can never have it they view it all as rape instead of seduction.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Anecdotes recounting his relentless drive for the acquisition of power abound and they date from his earliest years: While a student at San Marcos College, he realized that all the funding for student activities was controlled by a group called the Black Stars who rejected him as a member. So he set about creating an entirely new campus organization called the White Stars and by his senior year, he had succeeded in wresting control of student activities from his rivals.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And much is made of the ‘Johnson treatment’, his relentless way of literally physically trapping legislators by buttonholing them or cornering them in the Senate cloakroom and then cajoling, manipulating or brutally strong arming them into doing what he wanted. But he also used more subtle means to achieve his ends. For instance, the extending of small favors and courtesies was also a favored technique:  He would often carry a 75 cent cigar in his pocket because he knew Senator Carl Hayden loved good cigars. Or when he heard that Senator Harry Byrd’s daughter had died suddenly, he drove down to Virginia from Washington for the funeral. He was the only other Senator there. This endeared him to Byrd for years afterward.&lt;/p&gt;
